Since our advent, we have stood by the belief that 'menstruation' is as natural and basic as 'breathing'. And that has been our approach to providing for safe and sustainable menstrual hygiene means to all menstruators. This #MenstrualHygieneDay , our campaign- #BeLead - is aimed at generating awareness on the evolution of periods over the decades. #MenstrualHygieneDay is celebrated around the world with the aim to break taboos around menstruation, raise awareness about menstruation, and further, to drive away period poverty. We urge our audience to partake in this cause and stand with us in this initiative of making periods easy for all menstruators. 🙌

"My journey with Pee Safe started 4 years ago and thanks to my family, especially my husband and my mother in law, without their support this just wouldn't have been possible. When I joined here I didn't know much about the work or anything that was required to sustain here, but I started from scratch and today I've been able to reach a position where I can enable others to do the same. 

My team is my backbone, they've always been my biggest supporters. With Pee Safe, I was able to find a family outside my home, and I'm really grateful for them. They're always there for me whenever I need their help and I try to do the same for them. Even at times when I have to leave early from work, my team would just understand, they would know what's needed to be done and they would do it, without any question. Without such amazing fellows around, it would've been really difficult for me to reach at this point in my professional career. We've faced several hardships together, lots of rough phases too, but we never gave into the pressure and focused on what's important and with time things got better, we learned a lot of things which helped us all grow as better human beings, which in turn helped us do better at our work!

Now when I look at myself in the mirror, I see a confident and powerful woman looking back at me. It gives me immense joy to say that I'm one of the women behind this marvelous brand."

“It comes as a surprise to most people, but I’m actually the first one in my family & extended family to have the privilege of travelling outside Gwalior to work. Most people in my family were against the idea of me travelling for work or study, but it was my parents who stood up for me. They put up with their judgments & comments while encouraging me to keep doing what I was doing. It feels very empowering when my father asks for help in making essential decisions for his business, it makes me feel valued and important. I always keep him updated about the things I do & he further cheers me up by saying, ‘Very good beta! Aur acha karo!’. It has only because of my parents’ support that I learned how to deal with criticism.
I was in my second year at college when I started interning with Pee Safe. I didn’t have any plans for getting a job, but my internship with Pee Safe went so smoothly, there was so much to learn, & an immense capacity for growth, that I ended up staying here for long & the journey from an intern to an employee was complete. I would also give some credit to my ability to keep a track of my tasks and following up when necessary. I had several job opportunities from my father & his friends, but I wanted to do something on my own. Coming to a city like Gurgaon, was a challenge, but things kept falling into place and now looking back I can’t even remember what I was worried about. 
It feels really great to know that the products that I helped develop are reaching a majority of people and are making their lives easier. I feel immensely proud & happy to say, that I’m one of the women behind this amazing brand.”
.
.
.

"For most part of my life I was either called someone’s daughter, sister, wife, or mother, but what people fail to understand is that I have my own identity as well. I am my own person and I work hard every single day to make my mark. Even after all the efforts, I put in at home and work, there are people in my life who instead of encouraging, keep questioning my abilities as to how a mother of two will manage her home and her profession. I look at my work as an extended family, being the Head of the HR Department, I am accountable for the well being of all the employees. My career at Pee Safe started when the team only had 2 employees, fast forward to now we have a team of over 400+ professionals. At my workplace, people acknowledge the work that I do and look up to me as not just a boss-lady or a woman leader, but a headstrong, trustworthy & responsible leader. 

Even during the tough phases of my life, both of my families and especially my partner helped & motivated me a lot to do my best and eventually it did lead to some great outcomes. Especially during my second pregnancy, my colleagues & mentors at Pee Safe went out of their way to support me, that time has been quite unforgettable for me. This company, this brand has been a huge boost in my personal & professional growth, and most importantly my happiness. I feel proud in saying that I’m one of the Women behind this spectacular brand."
#TogetherWeRise #WomenBehindTheBrand

Ever feel like your period brings more than just cramps? That’s called period flu! It’s when you experience flu-like symptoms like fatigue, muscle aches, headaches, chills, nausea, and even swollen breasts during your cycle. It’s your body’s response to hormonal changes and inflammation. While it’s common, it’s still exhausting. Rest, hydrate, and listen to your body—it needs extra care and attention during periods.

Here’s the explanation to your thoughts 💭 

1️⃣ Trim your nails – The vaginal walls are sensitive, and long nails can cause discomfort or even small scratches during insertion. Since inserting a menstrual cup requires folding and positioning, short nails make the process smoother and safer.

2️⃣ Can it get lost inside? – The menstrual cup cannot get lost inside your body because the cervix acts as a barrier. The cervix is the narrow, lower part of the uterus that only allows fluids (like menstrual blood and sperm) to pass through. A menstrual cup sits below the cervix, inside the vaginal canal, and will not move beyond that point.

3️⃣ Can you pee with it inside? – Yes! The vagina and urethra are separate openings. The urethra (where urine exits) is located above the vaginal opening. A menstrual cup sits inside the vaginal canal and does not block the urethra, so you can urinate normally while wearing it. Some people may feel slight pressure on the bladder if the cup is positioned too high, but adjusting the placement can help.

4️⃣ Which hole should I insert it in? – The female anatomy consists of three openings: the urethra, vagina, and anus. The menstrual cup should be inserted into the vaginal opening, which is between the urethra (where you pee) and the anus (where stool exits). The vaginal canal is designed to expand and accommodate objects like a menstrual cup, tampons, and even childbirth.

Let’s see what lies behind the boob-

Fatty tissue- It helps determine the size of the breast and holds all the structures within the breast in place.
Lobules- They are responsible for producing milk for lactation.
Ducts- These are the tubes that carry milk from the lobules to the nipples.
Areola- It is a dark circular skin region around the nipple and has small bumps on its surface called Montgomery’s glands that secrete a protective oil, preventing chafing during breastfeeding. 
Nipple- It is at the centre of the areola. It contains smooth muscles that can cause the nipple to become erect. It also provides an exit for the milk release during breastfeeding.
